 founder Bill Gates\n> “Like geographic features (cities, mountains, rivers, etc.), species are sometimes named after prominent people. This species was named after Bill Gates in recognition of his great contributions to the science of Dipterology. Bill’s fly is only found in the high montane cloud forests of Costa Rica,” reads a text fragment explaining the association between Bill Gates’ name and an insect in Costa Rica.', 'id': 'lc_9e9077e4-13d1-49c8-809e-06a11e1dd89f'}], name='common_search', id='d352c1e6-1e40-4165-9325-16eef6a3ed4a', tool_call_id='call_0788b1864765471f850e3a43'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 155, 'prompt_tokens': 4167, 'total_tokens': 4322, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 113, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 155}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 4167}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-7301df7c-3f7b-9c7b-af66-b4d2796c2c3f', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd2-3fbe-7e42-b4ed-ed48a9e7dbd9-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"died January 8" 2021 museum founder'}, 'id': 'call_a5727e3174f643e5bb6c0062', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 4167, 'output_tokens': 155, 'total_tokens': 4322, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 113}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='fa8bcb07-1efc-4fe6-9be9-f5a5ecaca111', tool_call_id='call_a5727e3174f643e5bb6c0062'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 275, 'prompt_tokens': 4290, 'total_tokens': 4565, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 236, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 275}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 4290}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-6e668b62-3c5a-92d9-805d-9bc5164f436b', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd2-4aee-75a2-a53b-55c17b534d1d-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'marine species named after museum founder magazine publisher'}, 'id': 'call_9aac7696abbf496a82f6c0a7', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 4290, 'output_tokens': 275, 'total_tokens': 4565, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 236}}), ToolMessage(content="Published: 2024-07-05\nTitle: Automating Venture Capital: Founder assessment using LLM-powered segmentation, feature engineering and automated labeling techniques\nAuthors: Ekin Ozince, Yiğit Ihlamur\nSummary: This study explores the application of large language models (LLMs) in venture capital (VC) decision-making, focusing on predicting startup success based on founder characteristics. We utilize LLM prompting techniques, like chain-of-thought, to generate features from limited data, then extract insights through statistics and machine learning. Our results reveal potential relationships between certain founder characteristics and success, as well as demonstrate the effectiveness of these characteristics in prediction. This framework for integrating ML techniques and LLMs has vast potential for improving startup success prediction, with important implications for VC firms seeking to optimize their investment strategies.\n\nPublished: 2022-04-08\nTitle: Design of an Optimal Testbed for Tracking of Tagged Marine Megafauna\nAuthors: Talmon Alexandri, Roee Diamant\nSummary: Underwater acoustic technologies are a key component for exploring the behavior of marine megafauna such as sea turtles, sharks, and seals. The animals are marked with acoustic devices (tags) that periodically emit signals encoding the device's ID along with sensor data such as depth, temperature, or the dominant acceleration axis - data that is collected by a network of deployed receivers. In this work, we aim to optimize the locations of receivers for best tracking of acoustically tagged marine megafauna. The outcomes of such tracking allows the evaluation of the animals' motion patterns, their hours of activity, and their social interactions. In particular, we focus on how to determine the receivers' deployment positions to maximize the coverage area in which the tagged animals can be tracked. For example, an overly-condensed deployment may not allow accurate tracking, whereas a sparse one, may lead to a small coverage area due to too few detections. We formalize the question of where to best deploy the receivers as a non-convex constraint optimization problem that takes into account the local environment and the specifications of the tags, and offer a sub-optimal, low-complexity solution that can be applied to large testbeds. Numerical investigation for three stimulated sea environments shows that our proposed method is able to increase the localization coverage area by 30%, and results from a test case experiment demonstrate similar performance in a real sea environment. We share the implementation of our work to help researchers set up their own acoustic observatory.\n\nPublished: 2004-10-06\nTitle: Disabled Access for Museum Websites\nAuthors: Jonathan P. Bowen\nSummary: Physical disabled access is something that most museums consider very seriously. Indeed, there are normally legal requirements to do so. However, online disabled access is still a relatively novel field. Most museums have not yet considered the issues in depth. The Human-Computer Interface for their websites is normally tested with major browsers, but not with specialist browsers or against the relevant accessibility and validation standards. We consider the current state of the art in this area and mention an accessibility survey of some museum websites.", name='academic_search', id='921e495c-f50d-4220-abd6-43fc242956b3', tool_call_id='call_9aac7696abbf496a82f6c0a7'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 50, 'prompt_tokens': 4988, 'total_tokens': 5038, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 50}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 4988}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-e262ab18-dbcc-9abc-92ab-ac2b924816a1', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dd2-63e5-75a3-803c-74080b7b2a6c-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'wikipedia', 'args': {'__arg1': 'January 8 deaths 2021 2022 2023 museum founder'}, 'id': 'call_14b0ebd227e444eebf835c04', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 4988, 'output_tokens': 50, 'total_tokens': 5038, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Error performing Wikipedia search: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)', name='wikipedia', id='9aad919f-572e-4e11-b2d1-7e574f0901f9', tool_call_id='call_14b0ebd227e444eebf835c04'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 38, 'prompt_tokens': 5072, 'total_tokens': 5110, 'completi